#compdef viject
# =============================================================================
# viject — Create-React-App → Vite migration tool.  Walks a directory that
#          was created by the (deprecated and unmaintained-as-of-2023)
#          `create-react-app` scaffolder and rewrites its files so that
#          the project runs under Vite instead.  Specifically: rewrites
#          `package.json` scripts and dependencies (removing
#          `react-scripts`, adding `vite` + `@vitejs/plugin-react`),
#          generates a `vite.config.js`/`vite.config.ts`, relocates the
#          `index.html` entry from `/public/index.html` to the project
#          root with the right `<script type="module" src="/src/index">`
#          tag, rewrites JSX-in-`.js` to `.jsx` extensions (Vite is
#          stricter than webpack about this), updates `tsconfig.json` /
#          `jsconfig.json` for Vite's `moduleResolution`, and migrates
#          `setupProxy.js` and `setupTests.js` shims.  No CLI flags —
#          viject inspects the cwd's filesystem state via `getOptions()`
#          (looks for `tsconfig.json`, `.svg` files, `setupProxy.js`,
#          etc.) and asks the developer to confirm each migration step
#          interactively via @clack/prompts.
#
# Author:  bhbs (Hibarya Shibata — Japanese JS / Vite-ecosystem
#          contributor; author of viject and several other CRA-to-Vite
#          migration helpers)
# Source:  https://github.com/bhbs/viject
# CLI:     src/index.ts (uses @clack/prompts exclusively — no argv parser)
# Library: @clack/prompts (from natemoo-re/clack monorepo)
#          ("Effortlessly build beautiful command-line apps" — the JS
#           original that cliclack-rust R510 explicitly ports)
# License: MIT (viject); MIT (clack)
# Status:  Stable — 277+ stars on bhbs/viject; canonical recipe in
#          r/reactjs / dev.to for the CRA → Vite migration.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 35
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 35TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 34 to 35 documented libraries (@clack/prompts via viject).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=35, Go=35, TypeScript-Node=35 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 35
# RESTORED — perfect symmetry with R510 Rust=cliclack as Rust's Clack
# port).  Taxonomy now spans 251 cross-language CLI library variants
# across 60 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS @clack/prompts AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 35TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# @clack/prompts (https://github.com/natemoo-re/clack, 7819+ stars) is
# **Nate Moore's "Effortlessly build beautiful command-line apps"** — the
# JS-side reference implementation of the "modern minimal prompt" aesthetic
# that has reshaped how `create-X` tools look across the entire JavaScript
# ecosystem.  Nate Moore is an Astro core team member and the original
# author of Clack; @clack/prompts powers `npm create astro@latest`,
# `npm create svelte@latest`, the `create-vue` scaffolder, `create-next-
# app`, and the long tail of community `create-*` tools.  R510's
# cliclack (Rust) is a **deliberate port of Clack** to Rust; this
# completion documents the original.
#
# @clack/prompts is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library on
# FIVE specific axes:
#
#   1. INTERACTIVE-PROMPT-FIRST DESIGN (NOT AN ARGV PARSER) — @clack/
#      prompts is the FIRST TS-Node CLI library documented in this
#      taxonomy whose primary concern is INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS rather
#      than argv parsing.  Compare:
#         commander:            chained .command().option().action() argv parser
#         yargs:                chained .command(spec).demand().argv parser
#         oclif:                file-based + class-per-command framework
#         citty (UnJS):         defineCommand({meta, args, run}) argv parser
#         cac (R508):           zero-dep single-file 4-API argv parser
#         meow (sindresorhus):  JSDoc-driven static argv parser
#         minimist:             pure argv parser
#         sade:                 chained lightweight argv parser
#         arg (Vercel):         pure argv parser
#         mri (lukeed):         minimist replacement argv parser
#         yargs-parser:         parsing kernel
#         arg-parser:           typed plain object schema
#         cleye R472:           string-command map + typed flags
#         clipanion:            class-based with attribute decorators
#         gluegun:              extension-plugin architecture
#         stricli R484:         Bloomberg complex CLI framework
#         type-flag:            low-level typed flag primitive
#         tinyargs:             egoist's parser + Option class
#         breadc:               modern minimal TS framework
#         clerc R496:           plugin-driven typed chained API
#         brocli R500:          factory-fn + method-chain + plain object
#         command-line-args:    75lb's three-stage parser
#         cliffy (Deno-first):  chained + Promise-returning .parse()
#         gunshi R504:          universal-runtime + i18n + 3 renderers
#         cac (Egoist) R508:    zero-dep + single-file + 4 APIs
#         @clack/prompts:       INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS (no argv parser)
#      @clack/prompts-based binaries either have NO argv (viject,
#      create-honc-app, create-astro) or pair @clack/prompts with a
#      separate argv parser for "what to do" once parsed.  @clack/
#      prompts occupies a fundamentally different layer of the CLI-
#      library stack — **terminal-UX interaction**, not parsing.
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library whose primary concern is
#      INTERACTIVE-PROMPT UX rather than argv parsing.**  Parallel to
#      Rust's cliclack R510, but on the JS side; cliclack is in fact
#      a Rust port of THIS library.
#
#   2. JS-CLACK-AESTHETIC: THE "BEAUTIFUL MINIMAL PROMPTS" STANDARD —
#      @clack/prompts established the modern JS-ecosystem aesthetic
#      that competitive TUI prompt libraries (inquirer.js, prompts,
#      enquirer) had failed to deliver: minimal box-drawing-character
#      framing, soft cyan/green highlights, restrained banner intros,
#      consistent state symbols (◇ for active, ◆ for submitted, ▲ for
#      cancel, ▼ for error).  When `create-astro@latest` shipped with
#      Clack prompts in 2022, the JS community immediately recognized
#      the new aesthetic — and within a year every major `create-*`
#      tool had migrated.  Compare:
#        inquirer.js (SBoudrias, 21570*):  older, verbose, traditional
#                                           ASCII-bracket aesthetic
#        prompts (terkelg, 9282*):          minimal but no banner-frame
#                                           or unified state symbols
#        enquirer:                          extensible but slower
#        @clack/prompts:                    THE 2023+ MODERN STANDARD
#      Cliclack's existence as a Rust port is the **strongest possible
#      evidence** of Clack's design influence — first time a JS CLI
#      library has been faithfully ported to Rust as a primary CLI
#      library variant of its own.  Comparable cross-language flow:
#      gunshi R504 (Japanese-named TS lib influencing MoonBit's
#      admiral).
#
#   3. CHAINABLE BUILDER PER PROMPT TYPE — @clack/prompts exposes a
#      SEPARATE FUNCTION for each prompt type, each returning a Promise
#      of the typed user selection:
#         await text({ message, defaultValue, placeholder, validate })
#         await password({ message, mask, validate })
#         await confirm({ message, initialValue })
#         await select({ message, options: [{ value, label, hint }] })
#         await multiselect({ message, options, required, initialValues })
#         await groupMultiSelect({ message, options: { Group1: [...], ... } })
#         await selectKey({ message, options })  // single-keystroke
#         spinner()                              // returns spinner obj
#         taskLog(name)                          // returns logger obj
#         note(message, title)                   // boxed note
#         intro(banner)                          // session start
#         outro(banner)                          // session end
#         cancel(message)                        // graceful abort
#         log.info(msg) / log.warn(msg) /
#         log.error(msg) / log.success(msg) /
#         log.step(msg) / log.message(msg)
#      Each prompt accepts an options object and returns Promise<T> or
#      Promise<symbol> (the `isCancel(value)` discriminant detects
#      user-cancellation across the entire prompt set).  Compare:
#        cliclack Rust R510:    similar API surface — direct Rust port;
#                                 chainable builders instead of options
#                                 object, but same prompt-type-set
#        inquirer.js:            prompt(definitions[]) takes ALL prompts
#                                 as an array in one call — less
#                                 flexible than per-prompt awaiting
#        prompts (terkelg):      flat per-type-function API similar to
#                                 Clack but without unified theming
#        @clack/prompts:         options-object + Promise per prompt +
#                                 isCancel(value) discriminant —
#                                 idiomatic modern async TS DX.
#
#   4. `isCancel()` DISCRIMINANT VIA SYMBOL — @clack/prompts uses a
#      SHARED CANCEL SYMBOL returned by any prompt when the user
#      presses Ctrl-C or Escape:
#         const value = await text({ message: "Name?" });
#         if (isCancel(value)) {
#             cancel("Aborted");
#             process.exit(0);
#         }
#      The `isCancel(value)` function is a discriminant — if the user
#      cancelled, `value` is a sentinel `Symbol("clack.cancel")`; if
#      they answered, `value` is the typed answer.  Compare:
#        inquirer.js:    throws on Ctrl-C, caller catches via try-catch
#        prompts:        returns undefined on cancel, ambiguous with
#                         "no answer"
#        enquirer:       rejects Promise on cancel
#        @clack/prompts: SYMBOL DISCRIMINANT — type-narrow via isCancel
#                         predicate, idiomatic TypeScript-ergonomic
#                         cancellation handling.
#      The Symbol approach lets TypeScript narrow the type after the
#      `isCancel()` check — after `if (!isCancel(value))`, value is
#      narrowed to the typed answer.
#
#   5. `@clack/core` + `@clack/prompts` SPLIT (PROMPT-PRIMITIVE
#      ARCHITECTURE) — the natemoo-re/clack repo is a monorepo with TWO
#      packages:
#         @clack/core      — low-level prompt PRIMITIVES (Prompt class,
#                             TextPrompt, SelectPrompt, etc.; THEME-
#                             ABLE state machines with onKeypress
#                             handlers and submit/cancel events)
#         @clack/prompts   — opinionated HIGH-LEVEL API built on
#                             @clack/core (the text/select/confirm/etc.
#                             functions documented above)
#      Custom prompt designers extend @clack/core's `Prompt` class to
#      build their own primitives; consumers of the opinionated
#      aesthetic use @clack/prompts directly.  Compare:
#        cac (R508):           single file, no core/prompts split
#        commander:            single file, no split
#        inquirer.js:          custom-prompts via plugin system, not
#                               two-package split
#        @clack/prompts:       CORE+PROMPTS two-package layered design
#                               — letting third parties build their
#                               own opinionated layer on top of clack-
#                               core if @clack/prompts' aesthetic
#                               doesn't match.
#      This two-package split is the **mechanism that enabled cliclack
#      Rust R510 to be a port**: cliclack ports @clack/core's
#      primitive layer.
#
# Bonus: @clack/prompts has **TASK-LOG and SPINNER unified under the
# same banner/theme** — the spinner's `start()`/`stop()`/`message()`
# share the same render pipeline as text/select prompts, so a single
# `intro(banner)` → prompts → spinners → `outro(banner)` flow appears
# as one cohesive visual sequence.  Compare ora (the older standard
# JS spinner library) which is themeless and used SEPARATELY from
# prompt libraries.
#
# THE @clack/prompts API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   import {
#       text, password, confirm, select, multiselect,
#       groupMultiSelect, selectKey,
#       spinner, taskLog, note,
#       intro, outro, cancel, isCancel,
#       log, group,
#   } from "@clack/prompts";
#
#   // App framing:
#   intro("✨ My Tool");
#   // ... prompts ...
#   outro("All done!");
#
#   // Text input:
#   const name = await text({
#       message: "What is your name?",
#       placeholder: "Anonymous",
#       defaultValue: "Anonymous",
#       validate: (value) => {
#           if (!value) return "Required";
#           if (value.length > 50) return "Too long";
#       },
#   });
#
#   // Password input:
#   const pw = await password({
#       message: "Password",
#       mask: "*",
#       validate: nonEmpty,
#   });
#
#   // Yes/no:
#   const yes = await confirm({
#       message: "Continue?",
#       initialValue: true,
#   });
#
#   // Single-pick:
#   const pick = await select({
#       message: "Choose a framework",
#       options: [
#           { value: "astro",      label: "Astro",      hint: "recommended" },
#           { value: "next",       label: "Next.js",    hint: "" },
#           { value: "svelte-kit", label: "SvelteKit",  hint: "" },
#       ],
#   });
#
#   // Multi-pick:
#   const picks = await multiselect({
#       message: "Add features",
#       options: [
#           { value: "ts",       label: "TypeScript" },
#           { value: "tailwind", label: "Tailwind CSS" },
#           { value: "vitest",   label: "Vitest" },
#       ],
#       required: false,
#       initialValues: ["ts"],
#   });
#
#   // Grouped multi-pick:
#   const choices = await groupMultiSelect({
#       message: "Pick",
#       options: {
#           "Framework":   [{value: "astro", label: "Astro"}, ...],
#           "Database":    [{value: "pg",    label: "Postgres"}, ...],
#       },
#   });
#
#   // Cancel handling (must check every result):
#   if (isCancel(name)) { cancel("Aborted"); process.exit(0); }
#
#   // Spinner:
#   const s = spinner();
#   s.start("Installing dependencies...");
#   await doWork();
#   s.stop("Installed!");
#
#   // Boxed note:
#   note("Title", "Multi-line\nbody text");
#
#   // Log lines:
#   log.info("info message");
#   log.success("✓ success");
#   log.warning("warning");
#   log.error("error");
#   log.step("step name");
#   log.message("plain message");
#
#   // Group execution (run a series of prompts with type-safe acc):
#   const project = await group({
#       name:       () => text({ message: "Project name?" }),
#       framework:  () => select({ message: "...", options: [...] }),
#       ts:         () => confirm({ message: "Use TypeScript?" }),
#   }, {
#       onCancel: () => { cancel("Aborted"); process.exit(0); },
#   });
#   // project is typed as { name: string, framework: ..., ts: boolean }
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander           — chained .command().option().action() parser
#   * yargs               — chained .command(spec).demand().argv parser
#   * oclif               — file-based + class-per-command framework
#   * citty (UnJS)        — defineCommand({meta, args, run}) parser
#   * cac (R508, Egoist)  — zero-dep single-file 4-API parser
#   * meow                — JSDoc-driven static parser
#   * minimist            — pure parser
#   * sade                — chained lightweight parser
#   * arg (Vercel)        — pure parser
#   * mri (lukeed)        — minimist replacement parser
#   * yargs-parser        — parsing kernel
#   * arg-parser          — typed plain object schema
#   * cleye R472          — string-command map + typed flags
#   * clipanion           — class-based with attribute decorators
#   * gluegun             — extension-plugin architecture
#   * stricli R484        — Bloomberg complex CLI framework
#   * type-flag           — low-level typed flag primitive
#   * tinyargs            — egoist's parser + Option class
#   * breadc              — modern minimal TS framework
#   * clerc R496          — plugin-driven typed chained API
#   * brocli R500         — factory-fn + method-chain + plain object
#   * command-line-args   — 75lb's three-stage parser
#   * cliffy (Deno-first) — chained + Promise-returning .parse()
#   * gunshi R504         — universal-runtime + i18n + 3 renderers
#   * cac (Egoist)        — zero-dep + single-file + 4 APIs
#   * @clack/prompts      — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT library (functions
#                            + Promises + isCancel symbol + core/
#                            prompts two-package split + spinner/
#                            taskLog under unified theme)
#
# @clack/prompts occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **FIRST TS-Node CLI
# library documented whose primary concern is INTERACTIVE-PROMPT UX
# rather than argv parsing**.  Every other TS-Node CLI library
# variant in the taxonomy is an argv-parser of some flavor.  @clack/
# prompts is the OTHER axis of the CLI-library design space — terminal
# UX after argv has been parsed (or in the absence of argv entirely).
# Perfect symmetry with Rust's cliclack R510, which is in fact a port
# of THIS library.
#
# REAL-WORLD @clack/prompts USERS:
#
#   * bhbs/viject (THIS, 277*) — pure-clack CRA-to-Vite migration tool
#   * fiberplane/create-honc-app (115*) — pure-clack HONC stack
#       scaffolder (Hono + ORM + Neon + Cloudflare Workers)
#   * observablehq/framework (3498*) — Observable Framework static
#       site generator; uses parseArgs for argv + @clack/prompts for
#       interactive (e.g. `observable create` scaffolder flow)
#   * unjs/consola (7277*) — UnJS console-logger; uses @clack/prompts
#       for its `consola.prompt(...)` API
#   * di-sukharev/AI-TDD (276*) — TDD CLI with GPT code-gen
#   * atilafassina/quantum (528*) — Tauri + SolidStart starter
#   * johnlindquist/lamarck — Lamarck task framework
#   * kristoferlund/duet-gpt — paired-AI coding tool
#   * meitarbe/cognetivy — knowledge-graph CLI
#   * eznix86/w-share — file-share scaffolder
#   * felipebarcelospro/whatsapp-gpt-3 — WhatsApp + GPT-3 bot
#   * formspark/localview — local Formspark form viewer
#   * comet-ml/opik-openclaw (618*) — Opik observability OpenClaw
#       plugin
#   * fiberplane/create-honc-app (115*) — see above
#   * jonbon/jonbon — personal site framework
#   * Astro / SvelteKit / Vue / Next.js scaffolders (HISTORICAL —
#       `npm create astro@latest`, `npm create svelte@latest`, etc.
#       run their own create-X tools that internally use @clack/prompts)
#
# @clack/prompts' adoption pattern: **the de facto JS-ecosystem
# scaffolder UX standard since 2023**.  Every major framework that
# ships a `create-X` tool uses @clack/prompts.  CIs for monorepo
# tooling (bump-version, deploy, migrate) increasingly use it for
# interactive operator workflows.  Cross-language influence: cliclack
# Rust R510 ports @clack/prompts to Rust; future ports likely include
# Go and Python equivalents.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# VIJECT'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from bhbs/viject/src/index.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   viject
#
# viject takes NO command-line arguments.  When launched in a directory
# containing a `package.json` from a create-react-app scaffold, viject:
#
#   1. intro:    "Start migrating..."
#   2. spinner:  "Checking Git status" — aborts if uncommitted changes
#                (running `git status` under the hood).
#   3. spinner:  "Rewriting package.json" — removes `react-scripts`,
#                adds `vite` + `@vitejs/plugin-react`, rewrites
#                `scripts.start`/`scripts.build`/`scripts.test` for
#                Vite.
#   4. spinner:  "Rewriting d.ts files" — updates `src/react-app-env.d.ts`
#                to Vite's `vite/client` reference.
#   5. spinner:  "Writing vite.config.js" — only if neither
#                vite.config.ts nor vite.config.js already exists.
#                Generates appropriate vite.config with `@vitejs/plugin-
#                react`, optional SVG handling (`vite-plugin-svgr` if
#                .svg files were detected in src/), optional proxy
#                config (if package.json had a `"proxy"` field), test
#                config (if setupTests.js or setupTests.ts existed).
#   6. spinner:  "Moving index.html" — relocates `public/index.html`
#                to the project root with `<script type="module"
#                src="/src/index.{tsx|jsx}"></script>` rewrite.
#   7. spinner:  "Converting .js to .jsx" — rewrites JSX-in-`.js`
#                files to `.jsx` extension (Vite is strict about this).
#   8. outro:    "Migration complete! Run `pnpm install` (or `npm i`)
#                and `pnpm dev` to launch your app in Vite."
#
# Workflow:
#   $ cd my-cra-app
#   $ git status                        # ensure clean working tree
#   $ npx viject                        # interactive migration
#   $ pnpm install                      # rebuild lockfile + node_modules
#   $ pnpm dev                          # Vite dev server on :5173
#
# Since viject has NO flags, this completion file primarily exists to:
# (1) prevent shell errors when typing `viject`, (2) document the
# taxonomy entry above as the canonical TS-Node @clack/prompts
# reference, and (3) suggest completion for npx wrapper conventions.
#
# =============================================================================

_viject() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    # viject takes no CLI args - it's a pure interactive TUI.  Provide
    # default file completion in case a user passes a path which viject
    # itself would ignore.
    _arguments -C \
        '*: :_files' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_viject "$@"
